ges of vampires and cyborgs illuminate the contradictory processes of empowerment and exploitation that characterize the youth-consumer system. While the vampire is a voracious consumer driven by a hunger for perpetual youth, the cyborg has incorporated the machineries of consumption into its own flesh. Powerful fusions of technology and desire, these paired images symbolize the forms of labor and leisure that American society has staked out for contemporary youth. A startling look at youth in our time, Consuming Youth will interest anyone concerned with film, television, and popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBusiness. 0aConsumer behavior. 0aLiterature. 0aYoung adult consumers. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aconsumption, cultural studies, literature, literary study, american society, united states of america, usa, vampires, monsters, cyborgs, popular culture, youth, young, fiction, film, movies, books, cinema, mass media, capitalism, karl marx, objectification, consume, physical labor, empowerment, exploitation, technology, desire, symbolism, trauma, hyper-consumerism, leisure.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022646891440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226467023423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226467023/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles